Hi,
As far I understand, right now, if you want to use an FX in your game, then it has to go through the Content Pipeline, which will preprocess all macroses according to the Processor's Defines settings.
Such behavior is problematic if you have many defines in your FX code(which is often true for 3d engines), as you have to make an effect for every possible defines' set.
Therefore I propose to add the Effect compilation API to the framework.
Roughly speaking, I mean the addition of the function that takes FX code as input and produces the Effect bytecode as result.
Like following:

``` c#
byte[] simpleEffectByteCode = EffectUtils.Compile(Resources.MyShader, string.Empty);
Effect simpleEffect = new Effect(device, simpleEffectByteCode);
byte[] lightningEffectByteCode = EffectUtils.Compile(Resources.MyShader, "LIGHT=1");
Effect lightningEffect = new Effect(device, lightningEffectByteCode);
```

