There is a monogame windows directx project. There is a color texture with mipmap. I sample it in shader via sampler:
sampler colorSampler = sampler_state
{
    Texture = (colorMap);
    AddressU = CLAMP;
    AddressV = CLAMP;
    MAGFILTER = ANISOTROPIC;
    MINFILTER = ANISOTROPIC;
    MIPFILTER = NONE;
    MaxAnisotropy = 4;
};
With this one everything's fine.

But when I set MIPFILTER to point or something else to use mipmap all distant geometry fade in black. It looks like mipmap is not generated...

When attempting to draw text on the screen using a SpriteFont on iOS (and possibly other platforms), the result is seemingly random pixels on the screen where the text should be. This occurs with both SpriteFonts compiled to XNB format via the Content Pipeline on OS X, and prebuilt XNB fonts I found on the internet. Every time the program is run, the resulting pixels change slightly. In some cases, nothing is shown at all.

In my game, the code is as follows:

```
SpriteBatch SB = ...
SpriteFont font = Global.Content.Load<SpriteFont> ("Font");
SB.Begin();
SB.DrawString (font, "Hello world", new Vector2 (100, 100), Color.White);
SB.End();
```

This seemingly simple statement results a picture like the following:

![screen shot 2015-06-27 at 5 10 13 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4308047/8393877/087a5cbe-1cf0-11e5-84e3-0ab52b979561.png)

Notice the random pixels (with a large amount of green) in the top-left corner. I haven't the slightest idea what is happening.

This enables serialization of, for example,

```
public class MyCollection : Collection<T> {}

public class ClassToSerialize
{
    public MyCollection Children { get; set; }
}
```

where previously we only supported direct use of generic collection types:

```
public class ClassToSerialize
{
    public List<T> Children { get; set; }
}
```
